[2]
Date: Fri, 5 Sep 1997 10:24:27 -0500
From: Robert Rakita <rakita@heart.med.uth.tmc.edu>
I am certainly not the best person to discuss this (for example, Drs. Mason
and Kaplan, who have done many of the studies in this area, are just down the
street from me at Texas Children's Hospital), but I can provide some
information.
First, _S. pneumoniae_ is definitely the most common bacteria associated with
otitis media in kids. In most studies, it is found in 30-40% of all kids
with otitis media. The second most common organism recovered is _Haemophilus
influenzae_, with _M. catarrhalis_ a distant third.
Second, resistance of _S. pneumoniae_ to penicillin is a very well described
phenomenon. The prevalence of this has been increasing over the past 15-20
years in various parts of the world, with recognition of this in the US over
the past 5-10 years. There are usually two levels of resistance mentioned:
intermediate resistance refers to organisms for which the MIC of penicillin
is 0.1 - 1.0 ug/ml, while high-level resistance refers to organisms with a
penicillin MIC >1.0 ug/ml. There is some clinical significance to this
difference, as patients infected with intermediately resistant isolates can
often be treated with high doses of penicillin, while those with highly
resistant isolates are not. The prevalence of penicillin resistance varies
geographically, but overall is probably greater than 10% of isolates in the
US, the majority of which have intermediate resistance. However, the
prevalence of highly resistant isolates is increasing, and some of these are
also developing resistance to other antibiotics used for treatment, such as
third-generation cephalosporins.
Penicillin-resistant _S. pneumoniae_ is a well described cause of otitis
media.
---
Robert Rakita, M.D.
