[4]
From: Michael Green <greenm_at_chpsrv@chplink.chp.edu>
Date: Fri, 05 Sep 97 09:19:26 -0500
An increasing prevalence of _Streptococcus pneumoniae_ with decreased
susceptibility to penicillin have been recognized throughout the current
decade. The patterns of resistance are separated into "low-level resistance"
(with MICs against penicillin of 0.1 to 1.0 ug/ml) and "high-level resistance"
(with MICs > 1.0 ug/ml. It is for the most part assumed that these strains
will be resistant to first and second generation cephalosporins. In
addition, approximately 1/3 of these strains may also be resistant to 3rd
generation cephalosporins (e.g., cefotaxime or ceftriaxone). The mechanism of
penicillin-resistance in pneumococci is due to a change in the affinity of a
penicillin-binding protein for penicillin.
This is certainly not the first report of penicillin-resistant _S.
pneumoniae_ being recovered from the middle ear. Currently, it has been
reported that between 10 and 50% of middle ear isolates of pneumococci will be
resistant (approximately 1/3 low-level, 2/3 high-level). This varies with
the age of the child, prior exposure to antibiotics and attendance in day-
care.
The resistance tends to be found in those serogroups of pneumococci most
likely associated with clinical disease (e.g., SG 6, SG 19, SG 23, etc). The
resistance spread appears to be by diverse "clones" of bacteria, and not due
to spread of a single, resistant clone.
---
Michael Green, M.D.,M.P.H.
Division of Allergy, Immunology and Infectious Diseases
Children's Hospital of Pittsburgh
e-mail: <greenm@chplink.chp.edu>
