[5]
From: David A. Watson <dwatson@marlin.utmb.edu>
Date: Fri, 5 Sep 1997 09:13:17 -0500 (CDT)
Dr. Kelsey rightly points out that the pneumococcus is always the most
common, or one of the most common, bacterial causes of both acute and chronic
otitis media in children (see also work by Bluestone, Liu, Chonmaitree &
Howie, and others). Moreover, a number of investigators have clearly
demonstrated that nearly all cases of childhood otitis have an infectious
etiology. It is also correct to state that penicillin-resistant strains are
responsible for an increasing percentage of those childhood infections
caused by pneumococci (e.g., PC Appelbaum, Clin. Infect. Dis 15:77). Because
of the increasing frequency with which both intermediately and highly
penicillin-resistant pneumococcal strains are causing *acute* otitis media
(we certainly see them here in Galveston), one could easily extrapolate that
these same kinds of strains should be appearing with increasing frequency in
cultures of middle ear fluids from patients with *chronic* otitis media.
This was in fact first reported some years ago by Mills et al. (Clin.
Otolaryngol. 10(6):335-341).
It is important here, in my opinion, not to kill the messenger. What I mean
is that it is possible that many of the attendees at the meeting where the
findings of this study are being presented (American Academy of
Otolaryngology Head and Neck Surgery Foundation) will not have heard the
message that penicllin or even third-generation cephalosporin antibiotics no
longer constitute automatically effective prophylaxis or therapy against ear
infections due to pneumococci.
---
David A. Watson, Ph.D.
Asst Prof of Microbiology & Immunology
Dept of Microbiology & Immunology
University of Texas Medical Branch
TEL: (409) 747-0952
FAX: (409) 772-5065
e-mail: <david.watson@utmb.edu>
[I have no idea why the original report was considered sufficiently
innovative or unique as to be worthy of a press release. Clearly, penicillin
resistance is rapidly increasing in incidence among pneumococci. As a
result, there is increasing interest in serotyping of this organism. I
understand that the number of technicians in the CDC Streptococcal Reference
Laboratory has been reduced. At present, non-emergency requests for _S.
pneumoniae_ serotyping can be done in Dr. Watson's laboratory, which
routinely types isolates for a fee. Screening includes P disk screening,
bile solubility testing, macroscopic coagglutination serotyping, and quellung
reactions for typing within groups. This service might serve as a temporary
substitute for those who have no other means of having their pneumococci
(genus _Streptococcus_) isolates typed. -- Mod CHC]
